Here's how the kiosk uses the webapp chat code:

Kiosk uses the webapp via URL, not embedding
The kiosk opens a browser window, it doesn’t host or embed chat HTML itself.
Flow: User taps a contact in the kiosk → pywebview opens
http://localhost:8080/api/chat/entry?user_id=...&family_circle_id=...&sendbird_user_id=...&display_name=...
Server behavior: /api/chat/entry sets the session and redirects to /chat?sendbird_user_id=...&display_name=....
/chat is served by the same server as the webapp and returns chat.html + chat.js from the webapp.
So the kiosk uses the chat by loading the server’s /chat page in a webview. The server is shared between webapp and kiosk; the kiosk just navigates to URLs on that server.

Who uses which mode
Standalone (messages, status, etc.):

Direct visits to /chat
Kiosk opening /chat in pywebview
Embedded (chatMessages, chatStatus, etc.):

Only in checkin.html, where chat is shown inline on the check-in page.
chatMessages appears only on checkin.html, so embedded mode exists for that page. The kiosk never sees those IDs; it loads the standalone chat.html, which uses messages, status, etc.

About chat_embed.html
chat_embed.html in the kiosk folder is a separate, self-contained implementation and is not referenced by any route. The live flow uses the server’s /chat → chat.html + chat.js from the webapp.

Summary: The kiosk uses the webapp chat by opening /chat in a webview. The server serves chat.html and chat.js for that URL. Embedded mode is only for the check-in page; the kiosk uses standalone mode.